c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

void removeOuterParentheses(char *s, char *result) {
    int count = 0;
    int resIndex = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < strlen(s); i++) {
        if (s[i] == '(') {
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resIndex++] = s[i];
            }
            count++;
        } else { // s[i] == ')'
            count--;
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resIndex++] = s[i];
            }
        }
    }
    result[resIndex] = '\0';  // Null terminate the result string
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "(()())(())(()(()))";
    char result[100];  // Make sure this buffer is large enough
    removeOuterParentheses(s, result);
    printf("%s\n", result);
    return 0;
}

Aaaaand the student drops a 🔥 BANGER QUESTION 🔥 — I love it 😄💪

Short answer:
👉 No, C does not have a native string datatype like Java or Python.

Long answer (with some drama 🍿):

In C, strings are actually just arrays of characters (char[]), ending with a special null character '\0' to mark the end of the string.

For example:

c
char str[] = "Hello";

Under the hood, it’s stored like:

| 'H' | 'e' | 'l' | 'l' | 'o' | '\0' |

So in C:

  • You deal with character arrays.

  • No fancy StringBuilder or .length(). Instead you have strlen() (from <string.h>).

  • Modifying strings means modifying arrays directly.

  • And you must always remember the '\0' or you risk weird bugs 🤯.

ChatGPT said:

💣💣💣 BOOM!
Great question, detective! You just stepped on one of the most common C mistakes 🚩🚩

Main Problem:

You're returning result — which is a local array inside the function.

In C:

  • Local arrays (like char result[100]) are stored in the stack.

  • Once the function returns, the stack frame is destroyed — 💥 result becomes garbage memory.

  • So when you return result, you're returning a pointer to something that no longer exists.

👉 Undefined behavior (aka “surprise bugs party 🎉🐛”).

Other issue:

Inside your loop:

c
if (count > 0) { result[resultindex++] = s[i]; }

  • For '(' you increment count before checking count > 0.

  • So you're actually always adding '(', even for outermost opening.

  • The logic should be:

c
if (s[i] == '(') {
    if (count > 0) { result[resultindex++] = s[i]; }
    count++;
}

(Notice: check before increment for '(', check after decrement for ')')

🔥 Solution Options:

Option 1️⃣ — Use dynamic allocation (safe return)

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

char* removeOuterParentheses(char* s) {
    int len = strlen(s);
    char* result = (char*)malloc(len + 1);  // allocate memory dynamically
    int resultindex = 0;
    int count = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        if (s[i] == '(') {
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
            count++;
        } else {
            count--;
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
        }
    }
    result[resultindex] = '\0';
    return result;
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "(()())(())";
    char* output = removeOuterParentheses(s);
    printf("%s\n", output);
    free(output);  // free allocated memory
    return 0;
}

Option 2️⃣ — If you really want to use fixed-size, pass result array from caller:

c
void removeOuterParentheses(char* s, char* result) {
    int resultindex = 0;
    int count = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < strlen(s); i++) {
        if (s[i] == '(') {
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
            count++;
        } else {
            count--;
            if (count > 0) {
                result[resultindex++] = s[i];
            }
        }
    }
    result[resultindex] = '\0';
}

Then call like this:

c
char s[] = "(()())(())";
char result[100];
removeOuterParentheses(s, result);
printf("%s\n", result);

🔥 The expression:

👉 Goal: We’re copying characters from the end of s into the beginning of result.
Because we're reversing.

🧮 Let’s take an example:

Suppose s = "hello"
So:

Index (i)s[i]len = 5
0'h'
1'e'
2'l'
3'l'
4'o'

Now loop:

Loop iFormula len - i - 1s[len - i - 1]result[i]

💥 BOOM! Fully reversed string!

🔑 Why len - i - 1 ?

Because:

  • len gives total length.

  • i moves from start (0) to end (len - 1).

  • But we want to copy from end to start.

  • So:

"Wherever i is, take the mirror position from the end: len - i - 1."

👉 Mirror index formula! 🪞

🔥 When to use len - i - 1?

✅ Anytime you're reversing an array or string!
✅ Whenever you want to map:
first index → last index,
second index → second last,
third index → third last...

🎉 Funny way to remember:

"When you're reversing, think of a mirror. The leftmost dude becomes the rightmost dude. So for index i, his mirror twin is len - i - 1." 😄👯

🔥 FULL CODE 🔥

Here’s your C code, with love and friendship ❤️:

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <ctype.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Utility to reverse part of string from left to right indexes
void reverse(char *s, int left, int right) {
    while (left < right) {
        char temp = s[left];
        s[left] = s[right];
        s[right] = temp;
        left++;
        right--;
    }
}

char* reverseWords(char* s) {
    int len = strlen(s);
    char *result = (char*)malloc(len + 1);
    strcpy(result, s);  // Make a copy of original string

    // Step 1: Reverse whole string
    reverse(result, 0, len - 1);

    // Step 2: Reverse each word
    int start = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i <= len; i++) {
        if (result[i] == ' ' || result[i] == '\0') {
            reverse(result, start, i - 1);
            start = i + 1;
        }
    }

    return result;
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "hello world I am Asma";
    char* output = reverseWords(s);
    printf("%s\n", output);
    free(output);
    return 0;
}

🔬 Explanation:

  • 🔄 reverse() function reverses characters between given indices.

  • ✅ First, reverse whole string.

  • ✅ Then reverse each word one-by-one by finding spaces.

🔥🔥🔥 OH SNAP!! YOU JUST UNLOCKED LEVEL 3 OF STRING NINJA 🥷!!!
This is the famous Trim + Reverse Words problem that makes even experienced coders sweat 💦

The problem you're facing:

Input: " hello world "
You want output: "world hello"
✅ No leading spaces
✅ No trailing spaces
✅ Only single space between words

🔥 WHAT YOU NEED TO DO 🔥

1️⃣ First: Trim the input string (remove leading & trailing spaces)

2️⃣ Second: Reduce multiple spaces to single space inside the string

3️⃣ Third: Reverse words using your previous logic

🔧 C doesn't have built-in trim() like Python or Java... so we build it ourselves 😄

FULL SOLUTION:

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <ctype.h>

// Utility to reverse part of string from left to right indexes
void reverse(char *s, int left, int right) {
    while (left < right) {
        char temp = s[left];
        s[left] = s[right];
        s[right] = temp;
        left++;
        right--;
    }
}

// Function to trim and reduce spaces
char* cleanSpaces(char* s) {
    int len = strlen(s);
    char* cleaned = (char*)malloc(len + 1);
    int i = 0, j = 0;
    
    // Skip leading spaces
    while (s[i] == ' ') i++;
    
    while (s[i] != '\0') {
        if (s[i] != ' ') {
            cleaned[j++] = s[i++];
        } else {
            // add one space
            cleaned[j++] = ' ';
            i++;
            // skip multiple spaces
            while (s[i] == ' ') i++;
        }
    }

    // Remove trailing space if exists
    if (j > 0 && cleaned[j - 1] == ' ') j--;
    cleaned[j] = '\0';
    return cleaned;
}

char* reverseWords(char* s) {
    char* cleaned = cleanSpaces(s);
    int len = strlen(cleaned);

    // Reverse full string
    reverse(cleaned, 0, len - 1);

    // Reverse each word
    int start = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i <= len; i++) {
        if (cleaned[i] == ' ' || cleaned[i] == '\0') {
            reverse(cleaned, start, i - 1);
            start = i + 1;
        }
    }

    return cleaned;
}

int main() {
    char s[] = "  hello world  ";
    char* output = reverseWords(s);
    printf("\"%s\"\n", output);
    free(output);
    return 0;
}

🧙‍♂️ The trickiest part is cleanSpaces() function:

✅ Skips leading spaces
✅ Reduces multiple spaces to single
✅ Removes trailing space

✅ You can write your own trim() like this:

c
char* trim(char* s) {
    int start = 0;
    int end = strlen(s) - 1;

    while (s[start] == ' ') start++;
    while (end >= start && s[end] == ' ') end--;

    int newLen = end - start + 1;
    char* trimmed = (char*)malloc(newLen + 1);
    strncpy(trimmed, s + start, newLen);
    trimmed[newLen] = '\0';

    return trimmed;
}

1️⃣ Allocate space for cleaned string:

c
int len = strlen(s);
char* cleaned = (char*)malloc(len + 1);

  • len = length of input string.

  • Allocate enough memory for output string.

2️⃣ Remove leading spaces:

c
while (s[i] == ' ') i++;

  • i starts at 0.

  • As long as s[i] is space, we keep skipping.

  • When we reach first non-space character, we stop.

👉 This effectively skips ALL leading spaces.

3️⃣ Start processing characters:

c
while (s[i] != '\0') {

  • Loop through remaining characters (until end of string).

4️⃣ If it’s not a space, copy it:

c
if (s[i] != ' ') {
    cleaned[j++] = s[i++];
}

  • If character is not a space:

    • Copy to cleaned string.

    • Increment both source i and destination j.

5️⃣ If it is a space:

c
else {
    cleaned[j++] = ' '; // add one single space
    i++;  // move forward in input string

    while (s[i] == ' ') i++;  // skip ALL following spaces
}

👉 This is the heart of reducing multiple spaces to one:

  • When we see a space:

    • We add exactly one space into cleaned string.

    • Then keep skipping any additional spaces (while (s[i] == ' ')).

✅ This way: " " becomes " ".

6️⃣ After loop: Remove trailing space if it exists:

c
if (j > 0 && cleaned[j - 1] == ' ') j--;
cleaned[j] = '\0';

  • Check if last char in cleaned string is a space.

  • If yes, we "delete" it by decreasing j.

  • Then terminate string with '\0' as usual.

InputOutput
" hello world ""hello world"

  • Then I clean between chairs (reduce multiple spaces),

  • And finally I wipe the corners (trailing spaces)." 😄
